00:03:38.371 --> 00:03:42.653
with orangutans, gorillas,
chimpanzees, bonobos

00:03:42.653 --> 00:03:46.123
just a very short time
ago in evolutionary time.

00:03:46.123 --> 00:03:47.656
And here's another way to look at it.

00:03:47.656 --> 00:03:49.437
In millions of years before present,

00:03:49.437 --> 00:03:53.139
there's certainly some
discussion about the time frame,

00:03:53.139 --> 00:03:56.444
but the very important
point to make here is that

00:03:56.444 --> 00:04:00.092
while we classified all
these species as great apes,

00:04:00.092 --> 00:04:02.774
the main difference between
chimpanzees and bonobos

00:04:02.774 --> 00:04:07.079
is less than 1% of their
amino acid sequence level.

00:04:07.079 --> 00:04:09.523
In fact, we are closer to
bonobos and chimpanzees

00:04:09.523 --> 00:04:11.688
than they are to gorillas.

00:04:11.688 --> 00:04:13.692
In fact, we are closer to chimpanzees

00:04:13.692 --> 00:04:16.488
than mice and rats are to each other.

00:04:16.488 --> 00:04:19.023
So really, the classification
should be like this,

00:04:19.023 --> 00:04:22.696
we are hominids, and
then among the hominids,

00:04:22.696 --> 00:04:25.545
the lineage is leading
to us, the hominins.

00:04:25.545 --> 00:04:28.994
So if you have a species that's 99%

00:04:28.994 --> 00:04:30.741
identical to us at the protein level,

00:04:30.741 --> 00:04:32.356
how could you possibly have anything

00:04:32.356 --> 00:04:33.722
that's different between them?

00:04:33.722 --> 00:04:35.314
And in fact, when I first
got into this field,

00:04:35.314 --> 00:04:38.694
I found out at the veterinarians that

00:04:38.694 --> 00:04:40.396
the primates center I went to were using

00:04:40.396 --> 00:04:42.216
Harrison's textbook of internal medicine,

00:04:42.216 --> 00:04:44.322
same textbook I'd used.

00:04:44.322 --> 00:04:46.291
So that made sense.

00:04:46.291 --> 00:04:47.675
But if you wanna say there's such a thing

00:04:47.675 --> 00:04:49.561
as a human-specific disease,

00:04:49.561 --> 00:04:52.291
it's got to be very common in humans,

00:04:52.291 --> 00:04:54.875
rarely reported in
closely-related species,

00:04:54.875 --> 00:04:55.901
now this is very important,

00:04:55.901 --> 00:04:57.817
I'm zooming in on this
clip, not about things

00:04:57.817 --> 00:05:01.516
that happened at distant
portions of evolution,

00:05:01.516 --> 00:05:04.555
even in captivity and could not
be experimentally reproduced

00:05:04.555 --> 00:05:06.440
in such species, and I should warn you,

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:09.644
I'm gonna talk about a few
really horrible experiments

00:05:09.644 --> 00:05:10.642
that were done a long time ago

00:05:10.642 --> 00:05:12.565
that will never be done again.

00:05:12.565 --> 00:05:15.687
So there's a caveat:
who do you compare with?

00:05:15.687 --> 00:05:18.041
In my opinion, reliable
information is limited

00:05:18.041 --> 00:05:22.227
to data on a few thousand
great apes in captivity

00:05:22.227 --> 00:05:25.482
which were cared for at
NIH-funded facilities,

00:05:25.482 --> 00:05:27.942
with full veterinary care,
probably better medical care

00:05:27.942 --> 00:05:31.949
than most Americans get,
and full necropsies.

00:05:31.949 --> 00:05:34.788
Sp this is a reasonable data
said to compare with humans.

00:05:34.788 --> 00:05:36.633
I think comparing with wild chimpanzees

00:05:36.633 --> 00:05:40.466
and self-domesticated
humans isn't that useful

00:05:41.697 --> 00:05:44.256
in this question that
we are trying to ask.

00:05:44.256 --> 00:05:46.219
So when I went to Yerkes Primate Center

00:05:46.219 --> 00:05:48.070
and other centers and asked, and said,

00:05:48.070 --> 00:05:49.314
"What's the commonest cause of death

00:05:49.314 --> 00:05:51.236
"in captive adult chimpanzees?"

00:05:51.236 --> 00:05:52.850
And they said, "Heart disease,

00:05:52.850 --> 00:05:54.170
"heart attacks, heart failures."

00:05:54.170 --> 00:05:56.287
So I said, "Oh, it's the same thing."

00:05:56.287 --> 00:05:58.946
But then my wife, Nissi
Varki, who's a pathologist,

00:05:58.946 --> 00:06:00.508
went to see what is going on.

00:06:00.508 --> 00:06:01.341
She came back and said,

00:06:01.341 --> 00:06:04.664
"You fool, it's mostly
a different disease!"

00:06:04.664 --> 00:06:07.335
And so we got together with
various experts across,

00:06:07.335 --> 00:06:10.040
including Kurt, and wrote
this article that says

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:13.965
Heart Disease is Common
in Humans and Chimpanzees,

00:06:13.965 --> 00:06:18.048
But is mostly Caused by
Different Pathological Processes.

00:06:18.048 --> 00:06:19.585
So in comparing these two species,

00:06:19.585 --> 00:06:22.232
amazingly, it turns out
that while we humans,

00:06:22.232 --> 00:06:23.641
essentially all of our heart attacks

00:06:23.641 --> 00:06:24.921
are due to what you heard about,

00:06:24.921 --> 00:06:27.985
atherosclerotic coronary
blockade in the arteries,

00:06:27.985 --> 00:06:29.645
chimpanzees do get atherosclerosis,

00:06:29.645 --> 00:06:33.506
but it rarely ever leads
to coronary thrombosis.

00:06:33.506 --> 00:06:35.787
Instead, they get this
very peculiar kind of

00:06:35.787 --> 00:06:39.954
scarring in the myocardium,
in the heart muscle, fibrosis,

00:06:41.569 --> 00:06:44.867
so-called interstitial myocardial
fibrosis in great apes.

00:06:44.867 --> 00:06:49.237
This gives rise to abnormal
rhythms, heart failure,

00:06:49.237 --> 00:06:51.517
and heart attacks, so it looks like humans

00:06:51.517 --> 00:06:54.510
but in autopsies, it's
a different disease.

00:06:54.510 --> 00:06:56.001
In fact, since we wrote this article now

00:06:56.001 --> 00:07:00.250
put this out, it's
become so well-recognized

00:07:00.250 --> 00:07:03.843
that interstitial myocardial
fibrosis is such a

00:07:03.843 --> 00:07:06.272
major common in captive
great apes in all the zoos

00:07:06.272 --> 00:07:09.857
that all the zoos led by Zoo
Atlanta have gotten together

00:07:09.857 --> 00:07:13.102
and found a network to figure
out what is this disease,

00:07:13.102 --> 00:07:16.205
and why is it killing all our great apes.

00:07:16.205 --> 00:07:19.055
And so there are two
mysteries to be solved.

00:07:19.055 --> 00:07:21.837
One is, why do we humans not often get

00:07:21.837 --> 00:07:24.101
this fibrotic heart
disease that's so common

00:07:24.101 --> 00:07:26.557
in our closest evolutionary cousins?

00:07:26.557 --> 00:07:29.238
Conversely, why do
great apes not often get

00:07:29.238 --> 00:07:30.694
the kind of heart disease we get

00:07:30.694 --> 00:07:32.083
that's so common in humans?

00:07:32.083 --> 00:07:33.958
Since we're genetically so similar,

00:07:33.958 --> 00:07:36.779
there must be a very
limited number of reasons.

00:07:36.779 --> 00:07:39.461
We'd immediately say, "Ah,
it's just cholesterol."

00:07:39.461 --> 00:07:42.710
In fact, cholesterol is the leading thing

00:07:42.710 --> 00:07:44.846
that pushes atherosclerotic heart disease,

00:07:44.846 --> 00:07:46.239
but look at this figure here.

00:07:46.239 --> 00:07:48.809
Above is the black line,

00:07:48.809 --> 00:07:50.803
chimpanzee levels of cholesterol.

00:07:50.803 --> 00:07:53.195
Even at birth and soon after
birth in the first decade,

00:07:53.195 --> 00:07:56.185
they're so high that they
should be on statins.

00:07:56.185 --> 00:07:58.964
And they have similar HDL levels.

00:07:58.964 --> 00:08:02.812
They have APOE4 ancestral
allele, higher Lp(a) levels,

00:08:02.812 --> 00:08:06.808
sedentary lifestyles,
hypertension, and so on.

00:08:06.808 --> 00:08:09.948
Now, to be fair, there are
some amino acid differences

00:08:09.948 --> 00:08:11.835
in those two very important proteins

00:08:11.835 --> 00:08:13.923
and that may be part of the story.

00:08:13.923 --> 00:08:16.433
So based on this kind of
work, Nissi Varki and I

00:08:16.433 --> 00:08:18.691
went to several of these primate centers

00:08:18.691 --> 00:08:21.907
and tried to learn more about
this biomedical differences.

00:08:21.907 --> 00:08:23.757
In this case, we're
focusing on differences.

00:08:23.757 --> 00:08:25.825
I wanna be clear, there
are many similarities,

00:08:25.825 --> 00:08:28.189
which I'm not gonna talk about.

00:08:28.189 --> 00:08:31.135
And so we, of course, worked
on sialic acid biology.

00:08:31.135 --> 00:08:32.826
That's another story for another day,

00:08:32.826 --> 00:08:36.449
but this article also talks
about those differences.

00:08:36.449 --> 00:08:37.871
So here's a list of candidates

00:08:37.871 --> 00:08:40.919
for human-specific diseases
that I call definite,

00:08:40.919 --> 00:08:43.438
meaning the data so far
suggest that long list.

00:08:43.438 --> 00:08:45.147
Obviously, I'm not going to
go through the whole list.

00:08:45.147 --> 00:08:47.129
I'll give you a few examples.

00:08:47.129 --> 00:08:49.457
The big one, of course,
that I mentioned is this

00:08:49.457 --> 00:08:52.485
remarkable difference in the
rates of coronary thrombosis

00:08:52.485 --> 00:08:55.308
was this interstitial myocardial fibrosis.

00:08:55.308 --> 00:08:57.507
In fact, spontaneous coronary thrombosis

00:08:57.507 --> 00:08:59.173
due to atherosclerosis
seems to be very rare

00:08:59.173 --> 00:09:01.711
in other animals, in the
absence of experimental

00:09:01.711 --> 00:09:04.469
genetic or dietary manipulations.

00:09:04.469 --> 00:09:07.207
And the human-specific mechanics,
undoubtedly as mentioned,

00:09:07.207 --> 00:09:10.268
have to do partly with
behavioral and dietary changes,

00:09:10.268 --> 00:09:13.206
although I'm looking forward
to the talk from Mike Gurvin

00:09:13.206 --> 00:09:16.577
on this hunter-gatherer heart disease,

00:09:16.577 --> 00:09:20.301
these amino acid changes
in these two proteins,

00:09:20.301 --> 00:09:21.898
and something I'm not gonna go into,

00:09:21.898 --> 00:09:24.981
genetic change in sialic
acid that seems to have

00:09:24.981 --> 00:09:28.261
made our immune cells much
more prone to inflammation

00:09:28.261 --> 00:09:29.781
and also contributes to the effects

00:09:29.781 --> 00:09:31.345
of red meat and heart attacks,

00:09:31.345 --> 00:09:34.310
but that's, of course, a specialized case.

00:09:34.310 --> 00:09:36.221
Here's another disease, malignant malaria,

00:09:36.221 --> 00:09:37.933
the big killer malaria.

00:09:37.933 --> 00:09:40.342
Horrible, horrible
studies done in the 1920s

00:09:40.342 --> 00:09:43.140
and 1940s in the Belgian Congo,

00:09:43.140 --> 00:09:45.651
two-way cross-transfusions
between chimpanzees

00:09:45.651 --> 00:09:49.358
and humans infected or
non-infected with malaria.

00:09:49.358 --> 00:09:51.825
No evidence of across infection.

00:09:51.825 --> 00:09:53.376
It turned out the parasites look the same

00:09:53.376 --> 00:09:55.449
but are different.

00:09:55.449 --> 00:09:57.494
Fast forward almost a century and work by

00:09:57.494 --> 00:10:00.639
CARTA member Francisco
Ayala and others showed

00:10:00.639 --> 00:10:04.568
that all the falciparum in
the world, this killer malaria

00:10:04.568 --> 00:10:07.305
belongs to a very small
plate in the midst of

00:10:07.305 --> 00:10:10.012
many, many, many other ape malarias.

00:10:10.012 --> 00:10:11.761
In fact, Barbara Han later showed

00:10:11.761 --> 00:10:14.552
that Plasmodium falciparum probably arose

00:10:14.552 --> 00:10:18.364
by a single transfer from
one gorilla to a human,

00:10:18.364 --> 00:10:20.838
sometime we don't know exactly when,

00:10:20.838 --> 00:10:22.586
a few tens of thousands of years ago.

00:10:22.586 --> 00:10:25.581
So Pascal Gagneuxa
summarized it like this.

00:10:25.581 --> 00:10:27.207
Ape malarias are very common,

00:10:27.207 --> 00:10:29.021
and because of the sialic acid change,

00:10:29.021 --> 00:10:31.205
I'm not going to go into,

00:10:31.205 --> 00:10:35.291
we escaped the target
and we had a free ride

00:10:35.291 --> 00:10:36.934
for a million years or so,

00:10:36.934 --> 00:10:40.886
but the parasites always win in the end.

00:10:40.886 --> 00:10:43.726
And finally the parasite
in that one transfer

00:10:43.726 --> 00:10:46.130
switched to bind the
human kind of sialic acid

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:48.256
and then, of course,
we spread to mosquitoes

00:10:48.256 --> 00:10:52.568
in our environment, and
the rest is history.

00:10:52.568 --> 00:10:55.048
Here's another one,
typhoid fever, big killer

00:10:55.048 --> 00:10:58.500
throughout human history
until very recently.

00:10:58.500 --> 00:11:02.807
And it turns out there's been
a host adaptation to humans.

00:11:02.807 --> 00:11:06.247
Again, most horrible
studies done in the 1960s,

00:11:06.247 --> 00:11:10.414
large doses of Salmonella type
fever given to chimpanzees.

00:11:11.456 --> 00:11:15.623
Survival was much better, and
they were much less sensitive.

00:11:16.727 --> 00:11:19.223
It turns out we can find
an explanation for this.

00:11:19.223 --> 00:11:21.013
There's a human kind of sialic acid

00:11:21.013 --> 00:11:22.917
shown on this side of the screen,

00:11:22.917 --> 00:11:23.861
and the other side of the screen,

00:11:23.861 --> 00:11:26.987
Gc is the chimpanzee type of sialic acid.

00:11:26.987 --> 00:11:28.689
And the typhoid toxin only binds

00:11:28.689 --> 00:11:31.069
to the human kind of sialic acid.

00:11:31.069 --> 00:11:34.612
And so using most models,
we can sort of show

00:11:34.612 --> 00:11:36.069
that this is what's going on,

00:11:36.069 --> 00:11:38.750
that we have the
sensitivity and resistance.

00:11:38.750 --> 00:11:42.263
Cholera, Robert Koch, the
famous microbiologist said,

00:11:42.263 --> 00:11:44.365
"Although these experiments
are constantly repeated

00:11:44.365 --> 00:11:47.355
"with material from fresh cholera cases,

00:11:47.355 --> 00:11:48.407
"our mice remained healthy.

00:11:48.407 --> 00:11:50.485
"We then made experiments
on monkeys, cats,

00:11:50.485 --> 00:11:52.292
"poultry, dogs, and other animals,

00:11:52.292 --> 00:11:54.398
"and we were never able
to arrive at anything

00:11:54.398 --> 00:11:57.277
"similar to a cholera process."

00:11:57.277 --> 00:12:00.907
So far, there's nothing
except a baby rabbit model.

00:12:00.907 --> 00:12:02.916
Of course, there's explanation for this.

00:12:02.916 --> 00:12:04.964
Now I've been talking mostly
about infectious disease

00:12:04.964 --> 00:12:06.358
from Jared Diamond and others,

00:12:06.358 --> 00:12:07.943
and if you look in the
bottom of the screen,

00:12:07.943 --> 00:12:10.061
you can see that certain
diseases like rabies

00:12:10.061 --> 00:12:12.714
can spread throughout many animals.

00:12:12.714 --> 00:12:15.396
And then eventually a disease
makes its way into humans

00:12:15.396 --> 00:12:17.074
and by what's called the red queen effect,

00:12:17.074 --> 00:12:20.337
becomes highly specialized on one species.

00:12:20.337 --> 00:12:22.272
And so some of this is not so surprising,

00:12:22.272 --> 00:12:25.033
but the fact is that
there are such diseases.

00:12:25.033 --> 00:12:27.960
There's one set of definite diseases

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:29.032
that are kinda interesting.

00:12:29.032 --> 00:12:32.082
These are gonorrhea,
various other organisms

00:12:32.082 --> 00:12:34.096
that infect newborns.

00:12:34.096 --> 00:12:36.856
But it appears that these
bacteria have done is

00:12:36.856 --> 00:12:40.511
invent the human kind of
sialic acid and coat themselves

00:12:40.511 --> 00:12:45.006
in what my colleague, Victor
Nizet, calls molecular mimicry,

00:12:45.006 --> 00:12:47.908
basically wolves in sheep's clothing.

00:12:47.908 --> 00:12:50.543
And they're very successful pathogens.

00:12:50.543 --> 00:12:52.752
Okay, so that's some examples.

00:12:52.752 --> 00:12:56.462
I haven't gone through all of
them human-specific diseases

00:12:56.462 --> 00:12:58.554
that seem to be human-specific.

00:12:58.554 --> 00:13:00.249
What about probable ones?

